library(ggplot2)

years <- 2017:2021
quarters <- 1:4
types <- c("Electric","Gas")

pge_years <- NULL

#load electricity and gas data and combine all years into one dataset
for (year in years) {
  if(year == 2021) {
    quarters <- 1:2
  }
    for(quarter in quarters) {
      for(type in types) {
  
  filename <- 
    paste0(
      "PGE_",
      year,
      "_Q",
      quarter,
      "_",
      type,
      "UsageByZip.csv"
    )

  print(filename)
  
  temp <- read_csv(filename)
  
  #convert electricity and gas to the same units
  if(type=="Electric") {
    temp <- temp %>%
    mutate(TOTALKBTU = TOTALKWH *3.41214) %>%
    select(-TOTALKWH, -AVERAGEKWH)
  }
  else {
    temp <- temp %>%
    mutate(TOTALKBTU = TOTALTHM *99.9761) %>%
    select(-TOTALTHM, -AVERAGETHM)
  }
  
  pge_years <- rbind(pge_years,temp)

  saveRDS(pge_years, "pge_years.rds")
}
}
}

#Filtering to just residential data
pge_filtered_residential_data <-
  pge_years %>% 
  filter(
    CUSTOMERCLASS %in% c("Gas- Residential","Elec- Residential")
  ) %>% 
  group_by(
    MONTH, 
    YEAR, 
    CUSTOMERCLASS
  ) %>% 
  summarize(
    TOTALKBTU = sum(TOTALKBTU, na.rm = T)
  ) %>% 
  mutate(
    DATE = paste(YEAR,MONTH,"01",sep="-") %>% as.Date()
  )
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'MONTH', 'YEAR'. You can override using the `.groups` argument.
#Plot residential data for 2017-2021
pge_chart_residential <-
  pge_filtered_residential_data %>% 
  ggplot() +
  geom_bar(
    aes(
      x = DATE,
      y = TOTALKBTU,
      fill = CUSTOMERCLASS
    ),
    stat = "identity",
    position = "stack"
  ) +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45)) +
  labs(
    x = "Month",
    y = "kBTU",
    title = "PG&E Territory Monthly Residential kBTUs Usage, 2017-2021",
    fill = "kBTU source"
  )

pge_chart_residential

#Filter to just 2019 commercial and residential data
pge_filtered_data_2019 <-
  pge_years %>% 
  filter(
    CUSTOMERCLASS %in% c("Gas- Commercial","Elec- Commercial","Gas- Residential","Elec- Residential")
  ) %>% 
  filter (YEAR == 2019) %>%
  group_by(
    MONTH, 
    YEAR, 
    CUSTOMERCLASS
  ) %>% 
  summarize(
    TOTALKBTU = sum(TOTALKBTU, na.rm = T)
  ) %>% 
  mutate(
    DATE = paste(YEAR,MONTH,"01",sep="-") %>% as.Date()
  )

pge_chart_2020

Gas and electricity usage changed minimally from 2019 to 2020, despite the COVID-19 pandemic. There was a slight drop in February 2020 as compared to February 2019, but after that it was fairly consistent with the previous year. I expected gas and electricity usage to decrease in 2020 because many businesses and office buildings were not open and using power, but it is possible that this dip was counteracted by an increase in at-home electricity and gas use. You can see that commercial gas and electricity use were slightly lower in 2020 than 2019. Its important to consider that this data only represents a part of California and not the whole country, where trends may have been different.
